What is Kotlin?

Kotlin : High Level Programming Language
     You -> Kotlin -> JVM -> Machine Code -> Computer


Kotlin supports multiple programming styles:

    Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)
    Functional Programming (FP)
    Procedural Programming

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Before Kotlin, Android development was mostly done in Java.

Java:

    String name = "John";
    System.out.println(name);

Kotlin:

    val name = "John"
    println(name)


Java is strictly OOP based language so everything can be written only inside classes
Kotlin allows us to write code without classes

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

How Kotlin code works ?

Kotlin code (source code) -> compiled by the kotlin compiler -> java bytecode
.kt file -> compiled -> .class file
this .class file is platform independent
Kotlin mainly runs on JVM

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    Your Kotlin Code
         ↓
    Kotlin Compiler
         ↓
     Bytecode
        ↓
       JVM
        ↓
    Machine Code
        ↓
       CPU
        ↓
    Program Runs

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Kotlin/JVM
    Most common.
    Kotlin -> Bytecode -> JVM
    Used for:
        Android
        Backend development


Kotlin Native
    Kotlin -> Native Machine Code
    No JVM.
    Directly creates machine code.
    Used for:
        iOS
        macOS
        Native applications


Kotlin/JS
    Kotlin -> JavaScript -> Browser
    Runs inside browsers.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

To print "Hello"

Step 1: Source code

    You write the kotlin code file ;

    Main.kt :
    fun main() {
        println("Hello")
    }


Step 2: Compilation

    kotlinc -> kotlin compiler

    When you run:
    kotlinc Main.kt
    the Kotlin compiler starts reading your source code.


Step 3: Lexical Analysis (Tokenization)

    The compiler breaks your code into meaningful pieces.


Step 4: Parsing

     Now the compiler checks grammar.

Step 5: Semantic Analysis

     Now the compiler checks meaning.


Step 6: Bytecode Generation

     Now the compiler generates:  Bytecode

     This is the MOST important step.

     Your Kotlin code:
        println("Hello")
     is transformed into JVM instructions.


     creates MainKt.class file


Step 7: JVM Starts

     java MainKt.class
     Now the JVM launches.


Step 8: Class Loading, Memory Allocation

    JVM now loads MainKt.class into memory.
    This process is called Class Loading

    Now JVM creates memory areas.
    JVM Memory :
        Stack
        Heap
        Method Area

Step 9: Finding main()

    The JVM looks for:
        fun main()

    This is the entry point.

    public static void main(String[] args) in java


Step 10: Execution Begins

    JVM starts executing bytecode instructions.

    Something like:
        LOAD STRING "Hello"
        CALL println

Step 11: Execution Engine

    JVM Execution Engine starts reading instructions.

    Interpreter Executes Initially
    JVM interpreter reads bytecode, translates and executes line by line

    JIT Detects Frequently Used Code
    The JVM notices and marks it as hot code.

    JIT Compiles Bytecode
    JIT converts JVM bytecode into native machine code.

Step 12: CPU Executes

    Finally: Machine Code -> CPU
    The CPU executes instructions.

    Now your monitor displays:
        Hello


