Why Kotlin ?

Java :
too much boilerplate code
NullPointerException
crashes fast

The requirements:

    Must run on JVM
    Must work with existing Java code
    Must be safer
    Must be shorter
    Must be modern

Result: Kotlin

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Problem 1: Boilerplate

Java:

public class User {
    private String name;
    private int age;

    // constructor
    // getters
    // setters
    // equals
    // hashCode
    // toString
}

Kotlin:

data class User(
    val name: String,
    val age: Int
)

Compiler generates:

constructor
getters
equals()
hashCode()
toString()


------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Problem 2: Null Safety

Java:
    String name = null;
    name.length(); // crash

Kotlin:
    var name: String = null

Compiler: Error
Not allowed.

If null is possible:
var name: String? = null

Kotlin forces you to handle it:
println(name?.length)

The compiler protects you before the program runs.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Problem 3: Extension Functions

Imagine Java's String class doesn't have a method you need.

In Java:

public class StringUtils {
    public static String greet(String str) {
        return "Hello " + str;
    }
}

Usage:
StringUtils.greet("John");

Kotlin:

fun String.greet(): String {
    return "Hello $this"
}

Usage:
"John".greet()

Looks like the method belongs to String.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Problem 5: Checked Exceptions

Java:

try {
    file.read();
}
catch(IOException e) {
}

Kotlin removed checked exceptions.
Less clutter.


